The World Health Organisation’s Director General, Dr Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus has declared COVID-19 to be a pandemic, on Wednesday, 11 March. A pandemic is a worldwide spread of a new disease. Today (Thursday, 12 March), the Minister of Health, Dr Zwelini Mkhize confirmed that the number of cases of COVID-19 in South Africa has risen to 17.  This is an additional four cases from yesterday. The cases are from the following Provinces:KwaZulu-Natal: One A 38-year-old male from Durban who lives in Turkey and was visiting his family in South Africa has tested postive . He had traveled to the UK and returned to SA on 7 March. Mpumalanga: One A 27-year-old female from Mpumalanga who had traveled to the United States. She returned to South Africa on 7 March. Gauteng: One A 43-year-old male from Johannesburg who had traveled to New York via Dubai and returned to South Africa on 8 March. Free State: One A 32-year-old male who came into contact with a Chinese businessman. This is the first case of local transmission as all others have been by patients who had travelled abroad. ” At this stage, all patients are in self quarantine and have mild to moderate symptoms. They are also on symptomatic treatment. Our tracing teams are now making a list and have started contacting individuals that have been identified as these patients contacts,” said Dr Mkhize.